Step 1: Create Project Folder

Open PowerShell / CMD / Git Bash and run:

mkdir my-docker-app
cd my-docker-app

This creates your project folder and moves inside it.

Step 2: Create Project Files

Inside my-docker-app, create these files:

my-docker-app/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── Dockerfile
└── .github/
    └── workflows/
        └── ci-cd.yml

Very important: .github is a folder name starting with a dot.

Step 3: Add app.py

Create file: app.py

Paste this code:

from flask import Flask

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "Hello from Docker CI/CD!"

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
Explanation
Flask → Python web framework
@app.route('/') → homepage route
return → text shown in browser
port=5000 → app runs on port 5000
Step 4: Add requirements.txt

Create file: requirements.txt

Paste:

Flask

This tells Docker / Python which package to install.

Step 5: Add Dockerfile

Create file named exactly:

Dockerfile

No extension

Paste:

FROM python:3.9-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
Dockerfile Explanation
Base Image
FROM python:3.9-slim

Uses lightweight Python image.

Working Directory
WORKDIR /app

Creates /app folder inside container.

Copy Files
COPY . .

Copies all project files into container.

Install Dependencies
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

Installs Flask.

Start Application
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

Runs app when container starts.

This line is correct.

Step 6: Create GitHub Workflow File

Create folders:

.github
workflows

Inside create file:

ci-cd.yml

Full path:

my-docker-app/.github/workflows/ci-cd.yml

Paste:

name: CI-CD Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Build Docker Image
        run: docker build -t my-docker-app .

      - name: List Docker Images
        run: docker images
YAML Explanation
Workflow Name
name: CI-CD Pipeline

Name shown in GitHub Actions tab.

Trigger Event
on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

Runs workflow whenever code is pushed to main.

Job Name
jobs:
  build:

Creates one job called build.

Runner
runs-on: ubuntu-latest

GitHub creates Ubuntu virtual machine.

Checkout Code
uses: actions/checkout@v4

Downloads repo code into workflow runner.

Build Docker Image
run: docker build -t my-docker-app .

Builds Docker image.

List Images
run: docker images

Shows built Docker images.

Step 7: Initialize Git Repository

Run:

git init
Step 8: Add Files
git add .

Adds all files.

Step 9: Commit Files
git commit -m "Added Docker CI/CD workflow"
Step 10: Create GitHub Repository

Go to GitHub.

Click:

New Repository

Name:

my-docker-app

Click Create Repository

Step 11: Connect Local Project to GitHub

Copy repo URL.

Example:

https://github.com/yourusername/my-docker-app.git

Run:

git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/my-docker-app.git
Step 12: Push Code
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Step 13: Check GitHub Actions
Click:
Actions tab  then CI-CD Pipeline Running automatically.
